======================================================================
PART A: WHY α₂=3 IS IMPOSSIBLE AT n=6
======================================================================

All 10 partitions of {0,...,5} into two triples:
  P_0: (0, 1, 2) | (3, 4, 5)
  P_1: (0, 1, 3) | (2, 4, 5)
  P_2: (0, 1, 4) | (2, 3, 5)
  P_3: (0, 1, 5) | (2, 3, 4)
  P_4: (0, 2, 3) | (1, 4, 5)
  P_5: (0, 2, 4) | (1, 3, 5)
  P_6: (0, 2, 5) | (1, 3, 4)
  P_7: (0, 3, 4) | (1, 2, 5)
  P_8: (0, 3, 5) | (1, 2, 4)
  P_9: (0, 4, 5) | (1, 2, 3)

Each partition {A, B} is both-cyclic iff T|_A is cyclic AND T|_B is cyclic.
T|_{a,b,c} is cyclic iff arc pattern is not transitive.
3 arcs among 3 vertices → 2 outcomes: transitive (2 of them) or cyclic (6 of them).
P(T|_A cyclic) = 6/8 = 3/4 for each triple.

Distribution of α₂ = #{both-cyclic partitions}:
  α₂ = 0: 17328 tournaments
  α₂ = 1: 10880 tournaments
  α₂ = 2: 4320 tournaments
  α₂ = 4: 240 tournaments

Distinct both-cyclic patterns (subsets of 10 partitions): 71
Patterns by size:
  Size 0: 1 distinct patterns, total 17328 tournaments
  Size 1: 10 distinct patterns, total 10880 tournaments
  Size 2: 45 distinct patterns, total 4320 tournaments
  Size 4: 15 distinct patterns, total 240 tournaments

Analysis: which 3-element subsets of the 10 partitions can be simultaneously both-cyclic?
  Feasible 3-subsets: 60 out of C(10,3) = 120

★ NO tournament has EXACTLY 3 both-cyclic partitions!
  But there are tournaments with ≥3 both-cyclic partitions (α₂=4 has 240).
  CONCLUSION: Having 3 both-cyclic partitions FORCES a 4th!

  Verification: #{α₂≥3' = #{α₂≥4: 240 = 240: True

