======================================================================
PART B: JACOBSTHAL PISANO = MATRIX ORDER THEOREM
======================================================================

THEOREM: For all odd primes p, the Jacobsthal Pisano period π_J(p)
equals the order of M = [[1,2],[1,0]] in GL(2, Z/pZ).

PROOF SKETCH:
  The Jacobsthal sequence satisfies J(n) = a^T M^n e_1 where
  a = [0, 1]^T, e_1 = [1, 0]^T. Actually:
  [J(n+1)] = M^n [J(1)] = M^n [1]
  [J(n)  ]       [J(0)]       [0]

  π_J(p) = smallest k with J(k) ≡ 0, J(k+1) ≡ 1 mod p
  = smallest k with M^k [1, 0]^T ≡ [1, 0]^T mod p
  = smallest k with M^k ≡ I mod p (if this also gives 2nd column right)

Verification: M^n [1,0]^T = [J(n+1), J(n)]^T mod p

  p = 3:
    ✓ M^n e_1 = [J(n+1), J(n)]^T mod 3 for n=1..8

  p = 5:
    ✓ M^n e_1 = [J(n+1), J(n)]^T mod 5 for n=1..19

  p = 7:
    ✓ M^n e_1 = [J(n+1), J(n)]^T mod 7 for n=1..19

  p = 11:
    ✓ M^n e_1 = [J(n+1), J(n)]^T mod 11 for n=1..19


Deriving M^n explicitly:
  M^n = [[a_n, b_n], [c_n, d_n]]
  Column 1: M^n e_1 = [J(n+1), J(n)]
  Column 2: M^n e_2 = [2J(n), J(n-1)] since M·e_2 = [2,0] = 2·e_1,
    and M^n e_2 = M^{n-1}(Me_2) = M^{n-1}[2,0]^T = 2M^{n-1}e_1 = 2[J(n), J(n-1)]

  So M^n = [[J(n+1), 2J(n)], [J(n), 2J(n-1)]]
  M^n = I iff J(n)=0 and J(n+1)=1 and 2J(n-1)=1
  J(n)=0 and J(n+1)=1 implies J(n-1) = (J(n+1)-J(n))/2 = 1/2
  So need 2·(1/2) = 1 mod p → always true if 2 is invertible (p odd)!

★ THEOREM PROVED: For odd prime p,
  order(M mod p) = π_J(p) because M^n = [[J(n+1), 2J(n)], [J(n), 2J(n-1)]]
  and M^n ≡ I iff J(n) ≡ 0 AND J(n+1) ≡ 1 (mod p),
  which is exactly the Pisano period condition.

Verification of M^n = [[J(n+1), 2J(n)], [J(n), 2J(n-1)]]:
  ✓ M^n = [[J(n+1), 2J(n)], [J(n), 2J(n-1)]] verified for n=1..14

======================================================================
PART B2: THE p=3 JORDAN BLOCK ANOMALY
======================================================================

At p=3: eigenvalues of M are roots of λ²-λ-2 = (λ-2)(λ+1).
Since 2≡-1 mod 3, this becomes (λ+1)² = 0 — DOUBLE ROOT!

M mod 3 = [[1,2],[1,0]]. Eigenvalue λ=-1≡2 mod 3.
Check: (M-2I) mod 3 = [[-1,2],[1,-2]] ≡ [[2,2],[1,1]] mod 3
(M-2I)² mod 3 = ?
(M-2I)² mod 3 = [[0, 0], [0, 0]]
Is it zero? True

★ CONFIRMED: (M-2I)² ≡ 0 mod 3. M has a Jordan block of size 2.
  Order of Jordan block J = [[λ,1],[0,λ]] in GL(2,F_p):
  J^k = [[λ^k, kλ^{k-1}], [0, λ^k]]
  J^k = I iff λ^k = 1 AND kλ^{k-1} = 0
  At p=3, λ=2: ord(2)=2, so λ^2=1. Need k·1=0 mod 3, i.e., 3|k.
  So order = LCM(ord(λ), p) = LCM(2, 3) = 6. ✓

★ GENERAL JORDAN BLOCK FORMULA:
  If M has a Jordan block at prime p (repeated eigenvalue),
  order = LCM(ord_p(λ), p) instead of just ord_p(λ).
  This happens iff p | disc(char poly) = 1 + 8 = 9, so p = 3.
  Indeed, 3 is the ONLY prime where M(2) has a Jordan block!

  Discriminant of λ²-λ-2: Δ = 1+8 = 9 = 3²
  Primes dividing Δ: only p=3
  So p=3 is the UNIQUE 'exceptional' prime for tournament matrix order!

