======================================================================
GRAND SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

THE THREE LAYERS OF TOURNAMENT TOPOLOGY:

Layer 1 (Euler/Topological): x = -1
  Transfer matrix M(-1) ∈ SL(2,Z), order 6
  I(P_k, -1) has exact period 6
  Ind(P_k) cycles through 6 homotopy types

Layer 2 (Combinatorial): x = 1
  I(G, 1) = #independent sets
  Fibonacci numbers at path graphs

Layer 3 (Arithmetic/Tournament): x = 2
  I(Ω, 2) = H (Hamiltonian path count)
  Transfer matrix M(2), order mod p = π_J(p)
  M(2) mod 3 = M(-1) mod 3 (the mod-3 unification)

THE BRIDGE: M^n = [[J(n+1), 2J(n)], [J(n), 2J(n-1)]]
  Connects Jacobsthal sequence to matrix dynamics
  Jacobsthal Pisano period = matrix order (proved)

THE EXCEPTIONAL PRIME p=3:
  Discriminant Δ = 9 = 3², only divisible by p=3
  Jordan block at p=3: order = LCM(ord_3(2), 3) = LCM(2,3) = 6
  Same period as SL(2,Z) element at x=-1!
  2 ≡ -1 mod 3 is the ROOT CAUSE of all period-6 phenomena

THE α₂ GAP AT n=6:
  α₂ = #{both-cyclic partitions of 6 into 3+3}
  Values: {0, 1, 2, 4} — 3 is IMPOSSIBLE
  Having 3 both-cyclic partitions FORCES a 4th
  This is a deep combinatorial constraint on 3-cycle arrangements
